I shared a post-apocalyptic concept once, I've not yet gone anywhere with it. Take a world where human anthro relations are relatively normalized and go The Road or Book of Eli on it to set the story. I like stories with characters and species that really reflect the transformative (not TF) effects the setting and plot have on them; in fact, most people favor stories where characters undergo some kind of change. I like the idea of the "feral" sergal design - the breastless one, anyway - being a sort of primitive trick of biology that's been dormant since the advent of technology and civilization with the aesthetically pleasing form, picrelated, being the norm. The story is narrated from the perspective of the protagonist, who notes physiological changes, biological regressions (ala wild hogs) in his sergal high school girlfriend/fiancé over the story's course. She becomes shorter and more gruff with him, increasingly impatient, feral, her breasts recede, she takes to different postures for quicker movement, becomes more apt to kill to survive and eat, among other things. It's not an easy story and I imagine it would be hard to read, but I absolutely LOVE it in concept.
